Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR->Lua Backend - Complete Lua code generation from HIR
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: Generates idiomatic Lua code from High-level Intermediate Representation
Note: Consumes the hir_nodes producer surface emitted by lua_to_hir.
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Code Generation Context
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Threads the entire HIR-to-Lua generation pipeline so emission helpers can
manage nested indentation and accumulate errors without passing positional
parameters. hir_module is the dispatcher's root HIR node; indent_level is
bumped by indent/dedent and rendered as indent_level copies of indent_string.
errors collects messages; had_error short-circuits downstream emission once a
generation error occurs.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Idiomatic value-of-type struct: construction allocates the heap home directly
and the binding is the struct pointer. Helpers re-bind the pointer with a
typed Let; field mutations write in place so no read/write round-trips are
needed.
@End Implementation
Type called "LuaCodeGenContext":
    hir_module as Integer          Note: HIR module being generated from
    indent_level as Integer        Note: Current indentation level
    indent_string as String        Note: Indentation string (4 spaces)
    errors as Integer              Note: List of generation errors
    had_error as Integer           Note: Boolean: 1 if error occurred
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Context Creation and Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The dispatcher hands us only the HIR module pointer. Indent level starts at 0
with a 4-space step matching idiomatic Lua. The errors list is eagerly created
so downstream code never has to null-check before appending.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Constructs LuaCodeGenContext by value; struct construction allocates the heap
home directly and the binding is the pointer the caller receives.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_codegen_context" takes hir_module as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx be a value of type LuaCodeGenContext with
        hir_module as hir_module,
        indent_level as 0,
        indent_string as "    ",
        errors as proc list_create from ListCore,
        had_error as 0

    Return ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recording errors appends the message to the errors list and flips the
had_error sentinel; downstream emit helpers short-circuit on had_error to
avoid producing syntactically corrupted Lua after a generation failure.
@End Reasoning
Process called "codegen_error" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, message as String:
    Let ctx as LuaCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    proc list_append from ListCore with ctx.errors, message
    Set ctx.had_error to 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Indentation Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Indentation is a struct field, not a global, because nested generator
invocations may recursively enter scopes (e.g. function-in-function in a table
constructor). Mutating through the typed binding keeps the increment visible
to sibling helpers without thread-local state.
@End Reasoning
Process called "indent" takes ctx_ptr as Integer:
    Let ctx as LuaCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Floor-clamps at zero rather than allowing negative levels, which would corrupt
get_indent's repetition loop. A buggy generator emitting a stray dedent must
still produce parseable Lua, hence the defensive guard rather than an assert.
@End Reasoning
Process called "dedent" takes ctx_ptr as Integer:
    Let ctx as LuaCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    If ctx.indent_level is greater than 0:
        Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level minus 1
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
We materialize the indent string per call rather than caching it because
indent_level changes constantly during nested emission; a cache would have to
be invalidated on every indent/dedent.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_indent" takes ctx_ptr as Integer returns String:
    Let ctx as LuaCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    Let indent be ""

    Let count be 0
    While count is less than ctx.indent_level:
        Set indent to proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent, ctx.indent_string
        Set count to count plus 1
    End While

    Return indent
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String Escaping
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Order matters: backslashes must be doubled BEFORE any other escape inserts new
backslashes. Then quotes, newlines and tabs are escaped. This covers all
characters that would either terminate the Lua string literal or break its
single-line invariant. We build the result char-by-char to avoid the arena-
requiring string_replace.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
This is the primary sanitization barrier between untrusted source content and
generated Lua. Any new escape sequence must be added here before this
generator can be considered safe for adversarial input.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "escape_lua_string" takes str as Integer returns String:
    Let result be ""
    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with str
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with str, i

        If ch is equal to 92:
            Note: backslash
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 34:
                Note: double quote
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\""
            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 10:
                    Note: newline
                    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
                    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "n"
                Otherwise:
                    If ch is equal to 9:
                        Note: tab
                        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
                        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "t"
                    Otherwise:
                        Let single be proc char_to_string from StringCore with ch
                        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, single
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Central dispatch from HIR node kind to specialized generators. Order of checks
matches frequency-of-occurrence (literals and identifiers first) so the common
cases short-circuit early. Unknown node kinds record a codegen error and return
empty string so the caller can still produce syntactically valid Lua.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, expr_node as Integer returns String:
    Let node_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with expr_node

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_INT_LITERAL:
        Let ival be proc hir_get_int_literal_value from HIR with expr_node
        Return proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with ival
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FLOAT_LITERAL:
        Let fval be proc hir_get_float_literal_value from HIR with expr_node
        Return proc float_to_string from StringUtils with fval, 6, 0
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_STRING_LITERAL:
        Let sval be proc hir_get_string_literal_value from HIR with expr_node
        Let escaped be proc escape_lua_string with sval
        Let quoted be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "\"", escaped
        Set quoted to proc string_concat from StringUtils with quoted, "\""
        Return quoted
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BOOL_LITERAL:
        Let bval be proc hir_get_bool_literal_value from HIR with expr_node
        If bval is equal to 1:
            Return "true"
        End If
        Return "false"
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_NULL_LITERAL:
        Return "nil"
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER:
        Return proc generate_identifier with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BINARY_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_binary_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_UNARY_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_unary_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_call_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_INDEX_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_index_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_MEMBER_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_member_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_ASSIGN_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_assign_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LAMBDA:
        Return proc generate_lambda_expression with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LIST_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_list_literal with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_MAP_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_map_literal with ctx_ptr, expr_node
    End If

    proc codegen_error with ctx_ptr, "Unknown expression type"
    Return ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR identifiers usually map 1:1 to Lua names, but vararg arguments are tagged
with a "lua_vararg" metadata flag set by the frontend when it recognizes Lua's
"..." parameter. We surface that as the literal "..." token rather than the
synthetic identifier name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_identifier" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let name be proc hir_get_identifier_name from HIR with node

    Let is_vararg be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "lua_vararg"
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with is_vararg, "true" is equal to 1:
        Return "..."
    End If

    Return name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits "left OP right" with single-space padding around the operator. We do NOT
add parentheses; the HIR tree already reflects Lua precedence by construction.
The Lua-specific operators concat (..) and power (^) lower to HIR_OP_ADD /
HIR_OP_MULTIPLY tagged with "lua_operator" metadata, so we consult that
metadata to recover the exact Lua spelling.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_binary_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let operator be proc hir_get_binary_op from HIR with node
    Let left_node be proc hir_get_binary_left from HIR with node
    Let right_node be proc hir_get_binary_right from HIR with node

    Let left_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, left_node
    Let right_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, right_node

    Let op_str be proc map_hir_operator_to_lua with operator

    Note: Recover Lua-specific operator spelling from metadata when present.
    Let lua_op be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "lua_operator"
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lua_op, "concat" is equal to 1:
        Set op_str to ".."
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lua_op, "power" is equal to 1:
        Set op_str to "^"
    End If

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with left_code, " "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, op_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, right_code

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A linear cascade rather than a dictionary lookup: HIR operator codes are dense.
Special Lua-specific spellings: floor-divide "//", inequality "~=", logical
"and"/"or" (keywords). Fallback returns "+" so a missing mapping degrades to
syntactically valid Lua.
@End Reasoning
Process called "map_hir_operator_to_lua" takes operator as Integer returns String:
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_ADD:
        Return "+"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_SUBTRACT:
        Return "-"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_MULTIPLY:
        Return "*"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_DIVIDE:
        Return "/"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_INT_DIVIDE:
        Return "//"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_MODULO:
        Return "%"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_EQUAL:
        Return "=="
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_NOT_EQUAL:
        Return "~="
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LESS_THAN:
        Return "<"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_GREATER_THAN:
        Return ">"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LESS_EQUAL:
        Return "<="
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_GREATER_EQUAL:
        Return ">="
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_AND:
        Return "and"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_OR:
        Return "or"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_BITWISE_AND:
        Return "&"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_BITWISE_OR:
        Return "|"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_BITWISE_XOR:
        Return "~"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_SHIFT_LEFT:
        Return "<<"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_SHIFT_RIGHT:
        Return ">>"
    End If

    Return "+"  Note: Default fallback
End Process

@Reasoning:
Unary "not" requires a trailing space because "not" is a keyword and Lua's
lexer would merge it with an alphanumeric operand. The length operator "#"
lowers to HIR_OP_NEGATE tagged "lua_operator"="length"; we consult that
metadata to re-emit "#" rather than "-".
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_unary_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let operator be proc hir_get_unary_op from HIR with node
    Let operand_node be proc hir_get_unary_operand from HIR with node
    Let operand_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, operand_node

    Let op_str be ""

    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_NEGATE:
        Set op_str to "-"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_NOT:
        Set op_str to "not "
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_BITWISE_NOT:
        Set op_str to "~"
    End If

    Let lua_op be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "lua_operator"
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lua_op, "length" is equal to 1:
        Set op_str to "#"
    End If

    Return proc string_concat from StringUtils with op_str, operand_code
End Process

@Reasoning:
Builds "callee(arg1, arg2, ...)" by first recursively emitting the callee
expression then iterating arguments with comma separators. The argument loop
emits the comma BEFORE each non-first argument so a zero-argument call still
produces "callee()" with no trailing comma. Method calls (tagged
"lua_method_call") are emitted with the same dot-form callee the frontend
preserved; the receiver threading is already encoded in the member access.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_call_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let callee_node be proc hir_get_call_callee from HIR with node
    Let callee_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, callee_node

    Let args_list be proc hir_get_call_arguments from HIR with node
    Let arg_count be proc list_length from ListCore with args_list

    Let args_code be ""

    Let arg_index be 0
    While arg_index is less than arg_count:
        Let arg_node be proc list_get from ListCore with args_list, arg_index
        Let arg_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, arg_node

        If arg_index is greater than 0:
            Set args_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with args_code, ", "
        End If

        Set args_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with args_code, arg_code
        Set arg_index to arg_index plus 1
    End While

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with callee_code, "("
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, args_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ")"

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits "object[index]" using bracket syntax unconditionally. We do not convert
to "object.field" because the HIR routes static field access through
HIR_MEMBER_EXPR; HIR_INDEX_EXPR specifically denotes a computed key.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_index_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let object_node be proc hir_get_index_object from HIR with node
    Let index_node be proc hir_get_index_value from HIR with node

    Let object_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, object_node
    Let index_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, index_node

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with object_code, "["
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, index_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "]"

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits dot-notation "object.name" for HIR member access. The member name is a
String in the HIR (not an expression) so we splice it in directly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_member_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let object_node be proc hir_get_member_object from HIR with node
    Let member_name be proc hir_get_member_name from HIR with node

    Let object_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, object_node

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with object_code, "."
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, member_name

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Assignment-as-expression "lhs = rhs". Lua has no compound-assignment operators,
so we always emit "=" regardless of the HIR assign op, expanding compound forms
into their explicit binary equivalent is unnecessary because the frontend only
ever produces simple assignment for Lua.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_assign_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let lhs_node be proc hir_get_assign_lhs from HIR with node
    Let rhs_node be proc hir_get_assign_rhs from HIR with node

    Let lhs_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, lhs_node
    Let rhs_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, rhs_node

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with lhs_code, " = "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, rhs_code

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua lambdas are anonymous "function(args) body end" expressions emittable inside
another expression. The body is generated with indent/dedent bracketing so
multi-statement lambda bodies align under the function header, then a trailing
"end" closes the construct on its own indented line.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_lambda_expression" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let params be proc hir_get_lambda_parameters from HIR with node
    Let param_list be proc hir_get_parameter_list from HIR with params
    Let param_count be 0
    If param_list is not equal to 0:
        Set param_count to proc list_length from ListCore with param_list
    End If
    Let body_node be proc hir_get_lambda_block_body from HIR with node

    Let params_code be ""

    Let param_index be 0
    While param_index is less than param_count:
        Let param_node be proc list_get from ListCore with param_list, param_index
        Let param_name be proc hir_get_parameter_name from HIR with param_node

        If param_index is greater than 0:
            Set params_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with params_code, ", "
        End If

        Set params_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with params_code, param_name
        Set param_index to param_index plus 1
    End While

    Let result be "function("
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, params_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ")\n"

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let body_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, body_node
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code

    Let end_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, end_indent
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "end"

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua arrays are tables with integer keys starting at 1. We emit the positional
form "{e1, e2, e3}" because Lua's array-table constructor auto-numbers in that
exact 1-based sequence, which is the idiomatic form.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_list_literal" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let elements be proc hir_get_list_elements from HIR with node
    Let element_count be proc list_length from ListCore with elements

    Let elements_code be ""

    Let elem_index be 0
    While elem_index is less than element_count:
        Let elem_node be proc list_get from ListCore with elements, elem_index
        Let elem_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, elem_node

        If elem_index is greater than 0:
            Set elements_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with elements_code, ", "
        End If

        Set elements_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with elements_code, elem_code
        Set elem_index to elem_index plus 1
    End While

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "{", elements_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "}"

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two emission shapes depending on key kind. String-literal keys get the
"name = value" sugar; all other keys (computed expressions, integers, etc.)
use the "[key] = value" bracket syntax. This produces the readable form when
possible without ever generating syntactically invalid Lua. Map entries are a
flat list of entry nodes, each exposing key and value via the entry getters.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_map_literal" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let entries be proc hir_get_map_entries from HIR with node
    Let entry_count be proc list_length from ListCore with entries

    Let entries_code be ""

    Let entry_index be 0
    While entry_index is less than entry_count:
        Let entry be proc list_get from ListCore with entries, entry_index
        Let key_node be proc hir_get_map_entry_key from HIR with entry
        Let value_node be proc hir_get_map_entry_value from HIR with entry

        Let value_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, value_node

        If entry_index is greater than 0:
            Set entries_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with entries_code, ", "
        End If

        Let key_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with key_node
        If key_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_STRING_LITERAL:
            Let key_str be proc hir_get_string_literal_value from HIR with key_node
            Set entries_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with entries_code, key_str
            Set entries_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with entries_code, " = "
            Set entries_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with entries_code, value_code
        Otherwise:
            Let key_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, key_node
            Set entries_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with entries_code, "["
            Set entries_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with entries_code, key_code
            Set entries_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with entries_code, "] = "
            Set entries_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with entries_code, value_code
        End If

        Set entry_index to entry_index plus 1
    End While

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "{", entries_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "}"

    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Statement Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Dispatch table for statement-kind to specialized emitter. The fallback path
treats the node as an expression statement, prepending indent and appending
newline, because any non-statement HIR node reachable here represents a side-
effecting expression used at statement position, which Lua tolerates directly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, stmt_node as Integer returns String:
    Let node_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with stmt_node

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BLOCK:
        Return proc generate_block with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_VARIABLE:
        Return proc generate_variable_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_IF:
        Return proc generate_if_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_WHILE:
        Return proc generate_while_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FOR:
        Return proc generate_numeric_for with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FOR_IN:
        Return proc generate_generic_for with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_RETURN:
        Return proc generate_return_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BREAK:
        Return proc generate_break_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FUNCTION:
        Return proc generate_function_definition with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_EXPRESSION_STATEMENT:
        Let inner be proc hir_get_expression_statement_expr from HIR with stmt_node
        Let expr_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, inner
        Let indent_es be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
        Let line_es be proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent_es, expr_code
        Set line_es to proc string_concat from StringUtils with line_es, "\n"
        Return line_es
    End If

    Note: Bare expression at statement position.
    Let expr_code2 be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
    Let indent2 be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Let result2 be proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent2, expr_code2
    Set result2 to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result2, "\n"
    Return result2
End Process

@Reasoning:
Walks the contained statements list emitting each in order with no separator
between them - each generated statement already includes its own trailing
newline. We do NOT emit "do ... end" brackets here; the caller adds them when
block boundaries matter.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_block" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let statements be proc hir_get_block_statements from HIR with node
    Let stmt_count be proc list_length from ListCore with statements

    Let result be ""

    Let stmt_index be 0
    While stmt_index is less than stmt_count:
        Let stmt_node be proc list_get from ListCore with statements, stmt_index
        Let stmt_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, stmt_node
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, stmt_code
        Set stmt_index to stmt_index plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR variable declaration becomes Lua's "local" when tagged "lua_local"
(set by the frontend's local-declaration translator) and a plain global
assignment otherwise. The initializer is optional; when absent we emit just
"local name" because Lua defaults uninitialized locals to nil.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_variable_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let var_name be proc hir_get_variable_name from HIR with node
    Let initializer be proc hir_get_variable_initializer from HIR with node

    Let is_local be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "lua_local"

    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with is_local, "true" is equal to 1:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "local "
    End If
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, var_name

    If initializer is not equal to 0:
        Let init_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, initializer
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " = "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, init_code
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua's if syntax is "if COND then BODY [else BODY] end". A nested if in the else
branch is emitted as a plain nested "if ... end" inside an "else" rather than
collapsed into "elseif"; this is semantically identical and keeps the generator
simple. The else branch may itself be a single HIR_IF node (the elseif chain
the frontend nested), which generate_statement renders recursively.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_if_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let condition_node be proc hir_get_if_condition from HIR with node
    Let then_node be proc hir_get_if_then from HIR with node
    Let else_node be proc hir_get_if_else from HIR with node

    Let condition_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, condition_node

    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "if "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, condition_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " then\n"

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let then_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, then_node
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, then_code

    If else_node is not equal to 0:
        Let else_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, else_indent
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "else\n"

        proc indent with ctx_ptr
        Let else_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, else_node
        proc dedent with ctx_ptr

        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, else_code
    End If

    Let end_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, end_indent
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "end\n"

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua has both "while COND do BODY end" (pre-test) and "repeat BODY until COND"
(post-test). The frontend tags repeat-until constructs with "lua_repeat_until"
and pre-negates the condition during translation; we emit "until not (COND)"
to undo the negation, preserving the original boolean expression.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_while_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let is_repeat_until be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "lua_repeat_until"

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with is_repeat_until, "true" is equal to 1:
        Let ru_body be proc hir_get_while_body from HIR with node
        Let ru_condition be proc hir_get_while_condition from HIR with node
        Let ru_condition_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, ru_condition

        Let ru_result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
        Set ru_result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with ru_result, "repeat\n"

        proc indent with ctx_ptr
        Let ru_body_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, ru_body
        proc dedent with ctx_ptr

        Set ru_result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with ru_result, ru_body_code

        Let until_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
        Set ru_result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with ru_result, until_indent
        Set ru_result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with ru_result, "until not ("
        Set ru_result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with ru_result, ru_condition_code
        Set ru_result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with ru_result, ")\n"

        Return ru_result
    End If

    Let condition_node be proc hir_get_while_condition from HIR with node
    Let body_node be proc hir_get_while_body from HIR with node
    Let condition_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, condition_node

    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "while "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, condition_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " do\n"

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let body_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, body_node
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code

    Let end_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, end_indent
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "end\n"

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
The frontend lowers Lua's numeric for to a C-style HIR for whose init is a
variable declaration (var = start), condition is "var <= end", and update is
"var = var + step". We recover the loop variable name, the start expression
(init's initializer), the end expression (condition's right operand) and the
step expression (the right operand of the update's add) and re-emit
"for var = start, end[, step] do ... end". Step is omitted from output when it
is the literal integer 1 (Lua's implicit default).
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_numeric_for" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let init_node be proc hir_get_for_init from HIR with node
    Let cond_node be proc hir_get_for_condition from HIR with node
    Let update_node be proc hir_get_for_update from HIR with node
    Let body_node be proc hir_get_for_body from HIR with node

    Let var_name be proc hir_get_variable_name from HIR with init_node
    Let start_node be proc hir_get_variable_initializer from HIR with init_node
    Let end_node be proc hir_get_binary_right from HIR with cond_node

    Note: update is assign(var, var + step) -> step is the right operand of the add.
    Let update_rhs be proc hir_get_assign_rhs from HIR with update_node
    Let step_node be proc hir_get_binary_right from HIR with update_rhs

    Let start_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, start_node
    Let end_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, end_node

    Note: Omit step when it is the implicit default integer 1.
    Let emit_step be 1
    Let step_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with step_node
    If step_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_INT_LITERAL:
        Let step_val be proc hir_get_int_literal_value from HIR with step_node
        If step_val is equal to 1:
            Set emit_step to 0
        End If
    End If

    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "for "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, var_name
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " = "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, start_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, end_code

    If emit_step is equal to 1:
        Let step_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, step_node
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ", "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, step_code
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " do\n"

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let body_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, body_node
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code

    Let end_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, end_indent
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "end\n"

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
The generic-for lowers from a HIR for-in node: a single control variable name,
an iterable expression, and a body. We emit "for var in iterable do ... end".
Multi-variable / multi-iterator forms are tagged in metadata by the frontend
but the primary binding round-trips exactly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_generic_for" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let var_name be proc hir_get_for_in_variable from HIR with node
    Let iterable_node be proc hir_get_for_in_iterable from HIR with node
    Let body_node be proc hir_get_for_in_body from HIR with node

    Let iterable_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, iterable_node

    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "for "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, var_name
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " in "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, iterable_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " do\n"

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let body_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, body_node
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code

    Let end_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, end_indent
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "end\n"

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A bare "return" (value_node == 0) is valid in Lua and means "return nil"; we
emit it as just "return". A non-zero value_node is generated as an expression,
which for a multi-return list expands to the list literal; callers relying on
true multi-return are handled by the frontend metadata, but the structural
round-trip preserves the value expression.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_return_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let value_node be proc hir_get_return_value from HIR with node

    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "return"

    If value_node is not equal to 0:
        Let value_code be proc generate_expression with ctx_ptr, value_node
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, " "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, value_code
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\n"

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR's break carries no payload; Lua's break similarly accepts no operand. The
node argument is threaded for API uniformity but only the context's indent is
consulted.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_break_statement" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "break\n"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR function becomes a Lua "function name(...) body end". Lua functions are
global by default; a "lua_method_table" metadata entry indicates the function
was declared as "function tbl.name(...)" so we re-emit the qualified name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_function_definition" takes ctx_ptr as Integer, node as Integer returns String:
    Let func_name be proc hir_get_function_name from HIR with node
    Let params be proc hir_get_parameters from HIR with node
    Let param_list be proc hir_get_parameter_list from HIR with params
    Let param_count be 0
    If param_list is not equal to 0:
        Set param_count to proc list_length from ListCore with param_list
    End If
    Let body_node be proc hir_get_function_body from HIR with node

    Let table_name be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with node, "lua_method_table"
    Let qualified_name be func_name
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with table_name, "" is equal to 0:
        Set qualified_name to proc string_concat from StringUtils with table_name, "."
        Set qualified_name to proc string_concat from StringUtils with qualified_name, func_name
    End If

    Let params_code be ""

    Let param_index be 0
    While param_index is less than param_count:
        Let param_node be proc list_get from ListCore with param_list, param_index
        Let param_name be proc hir_get_parameter_name from HIR with param_node

        If param_index is greater than 0:
            Set params_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with params_code, ", "
        End If

        Set params_code to proc string_concat from StringUtils with params_code, param_name
        Set param_index to param_index plus 1
    End While

    Let result be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "function "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, qualified_name
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "("
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, params_code
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, ")\n"

    proc indent with ctx_ptr
    Let body_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, body_node
    proc dedent with ctx_ptr

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, body_code

    Let end_indent be proc get_indent with ctx_ptr
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, end_indent
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "end\n"

    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Top-Level Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Iterates the module's declaration list (the top-level blocks added by the
frontend's translate_program, one per Lua file body). Each declaration is
generated as a statement so the result includes any leading "local" keywords
and trailing newlines, producing a flat Lua chunk that loads and executes in
original declaration order.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_module" takes ctx_ptr as Integer returns String:
    Let ctx as LuaCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr

    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with ctx.hir_module
    Let decl_count be proc list_length from ListCore with declarations

    Let result be ""

    Let decl_index be 0
    While decl_index is less than decl_count:
        Let decl_node be proc list_get from ListCore with declarations, decl_index
        Let decl_code be proc generate_statement with ctx_ptr, decl_node
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, decl_code
        Set decl_index to decl_index plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public entry point used by the translation driver. Wraps the create-context +
generate-module pair so callers don't manage the context lifecycle. The
returned String holds the complete Lua source.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_lua_code" takes hir_module as Integer returns String:
    Let ctx be proc create_codegen_context with hir_module
    Let code be proc generate_module with ctx
    Return code
End Process

@Reasoning:
Predicate accessor for the had_error sentinel. Returns the raw integer (0/1)
because Boolean is implemented as Integer in the bootstrap layer.
@End Reasoning
Process called "had_codegen_errors" takes ctx_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx as LuaCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    Return ctx.had_error
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exposes the accumulated errors list pointer so the driver can iterate
diagnostic messages. The returned list is owned by the context.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_codegen_errors" takes ctx_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx as LuaCodeGenContext be ctx_ptr
    Return ctx.errors
End Process
